\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces The norm form $N(\delta ) = S_\zeta (\delta )^2 - 5\,S_L(\delta )^2$ for $d = 5$, computed using the first 100 zeros of each function with Lorentzian weights $w(\gamma ) = 2/(\frac  14 + \gamma ^2)$. Panel\nonbreakingspace (a): the oscillating signal over $[0,200]$, showing that $N$ is overwhelmingly negative. Panel\nonbreakingspace (b): the local fraction of $\delta $-values where $N > 0$, computed in sliding windows across $[0,2000]$; the measure of the set where $N > 0$ is approximately $5.5\%$ over $[0,2000]$, consistent with the predicted $O(1/\sqrt  {d})$ density.}}{5}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:norm-form}{{1}{5}{The norm form $N(\delta ) = S_\zeta (\delta )^2 - 5\,S_L(\delta )^2$ for $d = 5$, computed using the first 100 zeros of each function with Lorentzian weights $w(\gamma ) = 2/(\frac 14 + \gamma ^2)$. Panel~(a): the oscillating signal over $[0,200]$, showing that $N$ is overwhelmingly negative. Panel~(b): the local fraction of $\delta $-values where $N > 0$, computed in sliding windows across $[0,2000]$; the measure of the set where $N > 0$ is approximately $5.5\%$ over $[0,2000]$, consistent with the predicted $O(1/\sqrt {d})$ density}{figure.1}{}}
